2; offers the entry of data, volume by volume in 3d, or surface by surface in 2d,
for the physical characteristics and after, the boundary conditions input data,
for Surfaces, Lines, Points, and initial conditions for VSLP;
These data may be constant or defined by a function written by the User.
Thus, it is possible to give the dependency of the mass, viscosity, forces, ...
on x,y,z or time or material, ...

The initial velocity and pressure may be given by constants or functions,
or recover from velocities-pressures previously computed at different times.

Choose 3; to solve a STEADY STOKES incompressible FLOW
A linear system of order d times the number of velocity nodes plus 
the pressure vertex number must be solved.
The conjugate gradient leads to less main memories than the Crout factorization,
but, may be not converge with small viscosities...

Choose 4; to solve an UNSTEADY STOKES incompressible FLOW
Many linear systems of order d times the velocity nodes number, plus 
the pressure vertex number must be solved.
The conjugate gradient leads to less main memories than the Crout factorization,
but, may be not converge with small viscosities...

Choose 5; to solve an UNSTEADY NAVIER-STOKES incompressible FLOW
          by an IMPLICIT time step method;
Choose 6; to solve an UNSTEADY NAVIER-STOKES incompressible FLOW
          by a FRACTIONAL time step method;
          On an exiting flow boundary, impose the convected velocity (option 2;)
These 2 options solve the same problem by different schemes.
The Fractional step method necessitates less main memories than 
the Implicit method.
The using of conjugate gradient in place of a factorization of the matrix,
also, necessitates less main memories.

On the examples of the documentation fluider.ps, the best efficient method
is with Taylor-Hood finite elements, fractional step, conjugate gradient.

It is possible to compute the errors if the velocity and pressure expression
are known. For that, before to solve the problem, it is necessary to give
the 2 user's functions:
DefFunc EXACT_VELOCITY(t,x,y,z,nocomp);
  If nocomp=1 Then
    EXACT_VELOCITY = (1+t*t) * (1-x*x) * (1-y*y);      {for example}
  Else
    EXACT_VELOCITY = 0;
  EndIf
EndFunc;
DefFunc EXACT_PRESSURE(t,x,y,z);
  EXACT_PRESSURE(t,x,y,z) = (1+t) * cos(Pis2*x) * cos(Pis2*y); {for example}
EndFunc;


